Branch: A branch is a parallel version of your repository. Used to develop features independently
git branch feature/login

Checkout: Switch to a different branch or commit
git checkout main

Clone: Create a local copy of a remote repository
git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git

Commit: A Snapshot of your changes in the repository
git commit -m "Add login feature"

Conflict: When a Git can't automatically merge changes from different commits or branches. You must resolve the diffrences manually.

Fetch: Download changes from a remote repository without merging.
git fetch origin

Fork: A personal copy of someonle else's repository, usuall on a platform like GitHub.

Index (Staging Area): The Index (also called the Staging Area) is where changes are prepared before committing.
git add file.txt

Merge: Combine changes from different branches.
git merge feature/login

Origin: The default name for your main remote repository. You can rename or have multiple remotes if needed.
git remote add origin https://github.com/user/repo.git

Pull: Fetch and merge changes from a remote repository
git pull origin main

Push: Upload your commites to a remote repository.
git push origin main

Rebase: Move or combine a sequence of commits to a new base commit.
git rebase main

Remote: A version of your repository hosted on the internet or network.
git remove -v

Repository: The database where you project's history is stored.
git init

Stash: Temporarily sabe changes that aren't ready to commit
git stash

Tag: Mark a specific commit as important, usually for releases
git tag v1.0

HEAD: is a reference to the current commit your working directory is based on. Usually points to the latest commit on your current branch.
git log --oneline

Upstream:
An "upstreamn" branch is the default branch that your branch tracks and pulls from, usually on a remote repository.
git push --set-upstream origin main